onversion" class=3D"wp-image-91909 lazyloading"></a><figcaption>To convert =
PSI to atm, simply take the psi value and divide it by 14.696 or 14.7.</fig=
caption></figure><p>The <strong>psi to atm</strong> conversion is an import=
ant unit conversion for scientists and engineers. Both psi and atm are unit=
s of <a href=3D"https://sciencenotes.org/pressure-definition-in-science/">p=
ressure</a>, which is force per unit area. PSI stands for pounds per square=
 inch (lb/in<sup>2</sup>), or more properly, pound force per square inch. M=
eanwhile atm is the abbreviation for atmosphere, where one atmosphere is ap=
proximately the Earth=E2=80=99s atmospheric pressure at sea level. It=E2=80=
=99s easy to convert psi to atm. Here is the formula, along with worked exa=
mple problems.</p><h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">psi to atm Formula</h3><p>=
The formula for converting psi to atm is:<div id=3D"mmt-178c34ae-e668-46a3-=
987f-862e4c9b7eb0_1" class=3D"mmt-178c34ae-e668-46a3-987f-862e4c9b7eb0 mmt-=
primary" style=3D"display: block;"><div id=3D"mmt-178c34ae-e668-46a3-987f-8=
62e4c9b7eb0_1_zone" style=3D"visibility: visible !important;"></div></div><=
/p><p class=3D"has-background" style=3D"background-color:#6dbed0"><strong>a=
tm =3D psi =C3=B7 14.696</strong></p><p>or</p><p class=3D"has-black-color h=
as-text-color has-background" style=3D"background-color:#6dbed0"><strong>at=
m =3D psi =C3=B7 14.7</strong></p><p>Which formula you use depends on how m=
any <a href=3D"https://sciencenotes.org/significant-figures-and-uncertainty=
/">significant digits</a> you=E2=80=99re carrying in your calculations.</p>=
<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">psi to atm Example Problem</h3><p>For exampl=
e, convert 65 psi to atm:</p><p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color">at=
m =3D (psi) =C3=B7 (14.7 atm/psi) =3D 65 =C3=B7 14.7 =3D 4.4</p><p>65 psi e=
quals 4.4 atm.</p><p>Note how the =E2=80=9Cpsi=E2=80=9D units cancel out in=
 the numerator and denominator. If you set up the pressure conversion incor=
rectly, the unit won=E2=80=99t cancel out. Also, not that the same pressure=
 in atmosphere is a smaller number than the pressure in pounds per square i=
nch. These are two easy way of checking your work.</p><p>Let=E2=80=99s try =
another example. Convert 30 psi to atm.</p><p> atm =3D psi =C3=B714.7 =3D 3=
0 =C3=B714.7 =3D 2.0 atm</p><p>So, 14.7 psi is about 2 atmospheres.</p><h3 =
class=3D"wp-block-heading">atm to psi Conversion</h3><p>It=E2=80=99s equall=
y easy converting atmospheres to pounds per square inch or atm to psi. Use =
the conversion factor:</p><p class=3D"has-background" style=3D"background-c=
olor:#6dbed0"><strong>psi =3D atm x 14.696</strong></p><p>For example, conv=
ert 50 atm to psi:</p><p>psi =3D atm x 14.696 =3D 50 x 14.696 =3D 734.8</p>=
<p>So, a pressure of 50 atmosphere is 734.8 psi. Once again, check you work=
. Expect a value in pounds per square inch to be more than 10x bigger than =
its equivalent value in atmospheres.</p><h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Refe=
